    The approximate cost of keeping this webpage online would depend on the hosting solution you choose. Here are some common options:

    Low-Cost/Free Options:

    1. Replit Hosting:

      • Free tier: Available for basic websites with limitations
      • Paid plans: Starting around $7/month with Replit Core

    2. GitHub Pages:

      • Free for static websites
      • No server-side functionality (would need to modify the contact form to use a service like Formspree)

    3. Netlify/Vercel:

      • Free tier: Generous limits for personal sites
      • Paid plans: Starting around $12-19/month if you need more resources

    4. Shared Web Hosting:

      • Budget providers: $3-7/month (companies like Hostinger, Namecheap)
      • Mid-range: $7-15/month (companies like DreamHost, SiteGround)

    5. Domain Name: $10-15/year (optional but recommended for a professional appearance)

    For Your Specific Website:

    Given that your website is relatively lightweight with minimal server requirements (just handling the contact form), you could host it for as little as $0-5/month using services like:

    • GitHub Pages + Formspree (free + free tier)
    • Netlify/Vercel (free tier would be sufficient)
    • Replit's free or Core plan

    If you want the most professional setup, I'd recommend:

    • Domain name: ~$12/year
    • Basic hosting: ~$5/month
    • Total annual cost: ~$72 ($60 hosting + $12 domain)

    How to host it in Replit free plan

    2 hours ago
    AK
    Hosting Your Website on Replit Free Plan

    You can deploy your website on Replit's free plan by following these steps:

    Step 1: Prepare Your Project for Deployment

    Your project is already well structured for deployment on Replit. The main thing to ensure is that your server is configured to listen on the port provided by Replit's environment.

    Step 2: Use Replit's Deploy Feature
    1. Make sure your app is running properly in the current development environment
    2. Click on the "Deploy" button in the top right corner of the Replit interface
    3. Choose "Deploy to Replit" from the options
    4. Give your deployment a name (this will be part of your URL)
    5. Click "Deploy"
    Step 3: Access Your Deployed Site

    After deployment is complete, your site will be accessible at:
    https://[deployment-name].[your-replit-username].repl.co

    Important Notes for Replit Free Plan:
    • Always-on Limitations: Free Replit projects "sleep" after a period of inactivity (about 1 hour without visits)
    • Wake-up Time: The first visitor after a sleep period will experience a 15-30 second delay as the project "wakes up"
    • Resource Limits: Free tier has limited processing power and memory
    • Uptime: Not guaranteed for mission-critical applications
    Email Functionality:

    For the contact form to work on the free plan, you might need to:

    1. Use a service like SendGrid, Mailgun, or EmailJS that offers free tiers
    2. Store the API keys securely in Replit's Secrets tool (already implemented in your project)

    How do I push these codes to Github repositroy

    2 hours ago
    AK
    Pushing Your Code to GitHub Repository

    Here's how to push your Replit project to GitHub:

    Step 1: Create a GitHub Repository
    1. Go to GitHub and sign in (or create an account if you don't have one)
    2. Click the "+" icon in the top-right corner and select "New repository"
    3. Name your repository (e.g., "amitesh-portfolio")
    4. Choose "Public" or "Private" visibility
    5. Don't initialize with a README, .gitignore, or license since you're importing existing code
    6. Click "Create repository"
    Step 2: Set Up Git in Your Replit Project

    Run these commands in the Replit Shell (click on "Shell" in the bottom panel):

    # Configure Git with your GitHub username and email
    git config --global user.name "Your GitHub Username"
    git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
     
    # Initialize Git repository in your project
    git init
     
    # Add all files to staging
    git add .
     
    # Commit your files
    git commit -m "Initial commit"
    Step 3: Connect to GitHub and Push

    Replace YOUR_USERNAME and YOUR_REPO_NAME with your actual GitHub username and repository name:

    # Add your GitHub repository as a remote
    git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO_NAME.git
     
    # Push your code to GitHub
    git push -u origin main

    You'll be prompted to enter your GitHub username and password. For the password, you'll need to use a Personal Access Token:

    1. Go to GitHub → Settings → Developer settings → Personal access tokens → Generate new token
    2. Give it a name, select "repo" permissions
    3. Generate the token and copy it
    4. Use this token as your password when prompted
    Step 4: Verify Your Repository

    Go to your GitHub repository page (https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO_NAME) to confirm that your code has been successfully pushed.

    How can I push my replit code to Github repository

    2 hours ago
    AK
    Push Your Replit Code to GitHub Using Replit's Interface

    Replit provides a built-in way to connect to GitHub that's simpler than using command line. Here's how:

    Method 1: Using Replit's Git Integration

    1. Open the Version Control panel:

      • Click on the Git/Version Control icon in the left sidebar (it looks like a branch)
      • Or use the "Tools" menu and select "Git"

    2. Initialize Repository (if not already done):

      • If your Repl isn't already a Git repository, you'll see an option to initialize it
      • Click "Initialize Repository"

    3. Connect to GitHub:

      • Click on "Connect to GitHub"
      • Authorize Replit to access your GitHub account if prompted
      • Select the repository you want to push to (or create a new one)

    4. Commit Your Changes:

      • Add a commit message describing your changes
      • Click "Commit & Push"
    Method 2: Using Replit Shell (if GitHub integration isn't available)

    1. Open the Replit Shell:

      • Click on "Shell" at the bottom of the screen

    2. Run these commands in sequence:

      # Configure Git
      git config --global user.name "Your GitHub Username"
      git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
       
      # Initialize Git repository
      git init
       
      # Add all files
      git add .
       
      # Commit changes
      git commit -m "Initial commit"
       
      # Connect to your GitHub repository
      git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO_NAME.git
       
      # Push code
      git push -u origin main

    3. Authentication:

      • When prompted for password, use a GitHub personal access token
      • Create one at GitHub.com → Settings → Developer settings → Personal access tokens
      • Select "repo" permissions when creating the token

  10. Google Sheets
    Google Sheets API allows you to read, write, and modify Google Sheets. This integration uses a service account for authentication, suitable for server-side applications.
    Authentication Setup
    const { google } = require('googleapis');
     
    const SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON = JSON.parse(process.env.GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON);
     
    const auth = new google.auth.GoogleAuth({
    credentials: SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON,
    scopes: ['https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets'],
    });
     
    const sheets = google.sheets({ version: 'v4', auth });
    Read from Google Sheets
    const SPREADSHEET_ID = 'your-spreadsheet-id';
    const RANGE = 'Sheet1!A1:B5';
     
    const response = await sheets.spreadsheets.values.get({
    spreadsheetId: SPREADSHEET_ID,
    range: RANGE,
    });
     
    const rows = response.data.values;
    if (rows.length) {
    rows.forEach(row => {
    console.log(row);
    });
    } else {
    console.log('No data found.');
    }
    Write to Google Sheets
    const SPREADSHEET_ID = 'your-spreadsheet-id';
    const RANGE = 'Sheet1!A1:B2';
    const VALUES = [
    ['Name', 'Score'],
    ['Alice', 95],
    ];
     
    const response = await sheets.spreadsheets.values.update({
    spreadsheetId: SPREADSHEET_ID,
    range: RANGE,
    valueInputOption: 'USER_ENTERED',
    resource: { values: VALUES },
    });
     
    console.log(`${response.data.updatedCells} cells updated.`);
    Service Account JSON

    The entire contents of your Google Cloud service account JSON key file. This includes all the necessary information for authentication.

    Creating a Service Account

    1. Go to Google Cloud Console and sign in with your Google account.
    2. Select an existing project or create a new one (Click project dropdown > "New Project").
    3. Navigate to "IAM & Admin" > "Service Accounts" in the left sidebar.
    4. Click "+ CREATE SERVICE ACCOUNT".
    5. Enter a name and optional description, then click "CREATE AND CONTINUE".
    6. Grant appropriate permissions (e.g., "Editor" for Sheets access), then click "CONTINUE".
    7. (Optional) Grant users access, or click "DONE".
    8. In the service accounts list, click the three dots next to your new account > "Manage keys".
    9. Click "ADD KEY" > "Create new key", choose "JSON" format, and click "CREATE" to download the key file.
    10. Go to "APIs & Services" > "Dashboard", click "+ ENABLE APIS AND SERVICES" up top.
    11. Search for and enable "Google Sheets API". Add "Google Docs API" if you're also using Google Docs.
    12. Open the JSON key file you downloaded, copy its entire contents, and paste it into this field.

    Remember to keep your key secure and never share it or commit it to Git. Follow the principle of least privilege when assigning roles.

    Getting a Spreadsheet ID

    1. Open the Google Sheet you want to access.
    2. Look at the URL in your browser. It will be in this format: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/SPREADSHEET_ID/edit#gid=0
    3. The SPREADSHEET_ID is the long string of letters, numbers, and hyphens between '/d/' and '/edit'.

    IMPORTANT: Granting Spreadsheet Access to Your Service Account

    1. Find your service account's email address in the JSON key file (look for "client_email").
    2. Open your Google Sheet.
    3. Click the "Share" button in the top right corner.
    4. In the "Share with people and groups" field, paste your service account's email address.
    5. Set the permission to "Editor" if you need write access, or "Viewer" for read-only access.
    6. Uncheck the "Notify people" box (optional).
    7. Click "Send" or "Share" (depending on your Google Workspace settings).
    GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON

    ];

    console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
     
    const rest = new REST({ version: '10' }).setToken(process.env.DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN);
    try {
    await rest.put(Routes.applicationCommands(client.user.id), { body: commands });

    console.error(error);
    }
    });
     
    client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;
     
    if (interaction.commandName === 'greet') {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    await interaction.reply(`Hello, ${user}!`);
    }
    });
     
    client.login(process.env.DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN);

    client.on('messageCreate', async message => {

    { name: 'Field 1', value: 'Value 1' },
    { name: 'Field 2', value: 'Value 2' }
    );

    Authentication setup
    const hubspot = require('@hubspot/api-client');
     
    const accessToken = process.env.HUBSPOT_ACCESS_TOKEN;
    const hubspotClient = new hubspot.Client({ accessToken });
    Fetch contacts
    const hubspot = require('@hubspot/api-client');
     
    const accessToken = process.env.HUBSPOT_ACCESS_TOKEN;
    const hubspotClient = new hubspot.Client({ accessToken });
     
    async function getAllContacts() {
    const allContacts = [];
    let after = undefined;
    let hasMore = true;
     
    while (hasMore) {
    const apiResponse = await hubspotClient.crm.contacts.basicApi.getPage(
    100,
    after,
    ['firstname', 'lastname', 'email']
    );
     
    allContacts.push(...apiResponse.results);
     
    hasMore = !!apiResponse.paging;
    after = hasMore ? apiResponse.paging.next.after : undefined;
    }
     
    return allContacts;
    }
     
    getAllContacts()
    .then(contacts => {
    contacts.forEach(contact => {
    console.log(`Name: ${contact.properties.firstname} ${contact.properties.lastname}`);
    console.log(`Email: ${contact.properties.email}`);
    console.log('---');
    });
    })
    .catch(err => console.error('Error: ', err));
    Access Token

    To get started, you'll need to create a private app in HubSpot. Go to Settings > Account Setup > Integrations > Private Apps. Create a new private app, select the necessary scopes, and generate your access token. Paste the token below.
